{"questionId":"9073015","questionHtml":"<p style=\"text-align:left;\">The escape velocity for an object at the surface of the Earth is <em>v</em><sub>esc</sub>. The diameter of the Moon is 4 times smaller than that of the Earth and the mass of the Moon is 81 times smaller than that of the Earth. What is the escape velocity of the object on the Moon?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">A. <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{2}{81}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n    <mn>81</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span><em>v</em><sub>esc</sub></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">B. <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{4}{81}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n    <mn>81</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span><em>v</em><sub>esc</sub></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">C. <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{2}{9}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n    <mn>9</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span><em>v</em><sub>esc</sub></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">D. <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{4}{9}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>4</mn>\n    <mn>9</mn>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span><em>v</em><sub>esc</sub></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>C</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9073015","referenceCode":"19M.1.HL.TZ1.33","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"The escape velocity for an object at the surface of the Earth is vesc. The diameter of the Moon is 4 times smaller than that of the Earth and the mass of the Moon is 81 times small","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"33","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields","10.2 – Fields at work","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 10: Fields"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}